<p>
The quarto proved to be a difficult format for this method of watermark capture, as the
marks in this format appear in the middle of the spine fold, and it's particularly difficult
to position the book under the camera in a way that allows for image capture down
into the gutter.  As these images demonstrate, the overhead lighting and the 
slight thickness of the NoUVIR paddle combine to cast a shadow into the gutter
that cuts off part of the visible area of the watermark.  When this truncation is
compounded by the fact that a piece of the watermark is invariably trapped 
within the binding itself, the results seem fragmentary indeed.  I've pieced 
together the marks from leaves 
<a href="javascript:newWin('http://etext.lib.virginia.edu/watermarks/1717c/compositeb.jpg', 'composite')">
chi1 and chi2</a> into a single image; although the 
reproductions are clear, a good third of the watermark is evidently missing.</p>

